<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-04-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="492" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                        <head>No. 37.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Sir <persName type="to">L. S. Sackville
                                    West</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Note verbale.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-04-21"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 21,
                                1888</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Responding to the note verbale of Sir Lionel West, dated the 18th
                            instant, it is suggested on behalf of the United States that, as the
                            cases of seizure of British sealing vessels in Behring Sea, therein
                            referred to, are now in court pending an appeal from a judicial
                            decision, it is preferable to await the judgment of the appellate court
                            in the premises.</p>
                    </div>
